## Why This Week Matters

Two converging forces define this week: a confirmed, active attack campaign targeting the exact identity and SaaS integration patterns most organizations have built over the past five years, and Microsoft's most significant shift in default authentication since the introduction of multi-factor login. Leadership must understand that these two stories are connected. The ShinyHunters campaign succeeds precisely because organizations still rely on passwords, shared credentials, and loosely governed third-party app connections. The move to passkeys and tighter OAuth governance is the direct architectural response. Organizations that act on both fronts this month will be measurably harder to breach and better positioned with auditors and insurers. Those that delay will find themselves on the wrong side of both the threat landscape and their compliance posture.

*Sources: [Microsoft Threat Intelligence — ShinyHunters OAuth Abuse](https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/security/blog/2026/07/13/defending-saas-based-applications-against-shinyhunters-oauth-abuse/) · [Microsoft Security Blog — Passkeys as Default in Entra ID](https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/security/blog/2026/07/13/microsoft-entra-id-security-updates-passkeys-are-the-default-authentication-method-in-entra-id/) · [Microsoft Secure Future Initiative — July 2026 Progress Report](https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/security/blog/2026/07/10/securing-our-future-july-2026-progress-report-on-microsofts-secure-future-initiative/)*

