## If You Take No Action

**ShinyHunters OAuth campaign — unreviewed SaaS and guest access:** Organizations that do not audit their third-party OAuth application permissions and guest account configurations this week remain directly exposed to the documented attack pattern. A successful OAuth abuse breach gives attackers persistent, often invisible access to email, files, and connected systems without requiring a password. Detection can take weeks. The downstream consequences include data exfiltration, regulatory breach notification obligations under GDPR and HIPAA, and potential cyber insurance claim complications if the insurer determines that a known, published threat was not acted upon.

**Passkeys as default — no preparation:** If your IT team does not prepare employees before passkey-based sign-in becomes the default experience, a significant portion of your workforce will encounter unfamiliar login prompts with no guidance. Users who rely on SMS codes may find their authentication method behaving differently or requiring re-enrollment under the new model. The practical result is avoidable help desk overload, potential lockouts during business hours, and a workforce that loses trust in a security improvement that was intended to protect them.

**GigaWiper and destructive malware — no endpoint and backup review:** The GigaWiper backdoor is designed to destroy data and mimic ransomware behavior. Organizations that have not confirmed complete endpoint detection coverage and tested their backup recovery procedures within the past 90 days have no reliable answer to the question of how quickly they could resume operations after a destructive attack. Cyber insurers increasingly require documented evidence of tested recovery procedures; the absence of that documentation affects both coverage and claim outcomes.

